# Akashi Sidebar UI/UX Rule

Use a solid, modern, Cursor-inspired look: compact layout, calm neutral surfaces, subtle borders, and one clear accent.

- Build UI with semantic tokens first (`--akashi-*` mapped to `--vscode-*` vars); avoid hardcoded hex colors when a VS Code variable exists.
- Keep spacing on an 8px rhythm (`4/8/12/16/20` allowed where needed for density).
- Prioritize hierarchy: overline/title/status, then key metric card, then actions, then helper text.
- Use consistent component states: idle, loading, success, error. Status labels must be explicit and short.
- Button hierarchy: one primary action per section, secondary actions visually quieter.
- During async work, disable conflicting controls and show clear progress text.
- Preserve accessibility: visible `:focus-visible`, semantic labels, high-contrast support, and reduced-motion fallback.
- Prefer CSS in dedicated files; do not add inline styles/scripts to webview HTML unless unavoidable.
- Keep sidebars uncluttered; avoid adding controls that are better represented as commands.
- Verify dark, light, and high-contrast themes before finalizing UI changes.

## Do / Don’t

- Do: use `var(--vscode-...)` tokens and semantic class names.
- Do: keep cards and actions visually grouped with clear separators.
- Don’t: introduce multiple accent colors in the same panel.
- Don’t: hide critical state in color only; pair color with text.
